# UDS Figma Component Inspection

When reading or syncing the **UDS Components** Figma file, do not rely on
screenshots as the source of truth.

Screenshots are useful for visual confirmation only. They are insufficient for
props, variants, states, anatomy, spacing, token usage, or CSS/spec updates.

## Canonical file

- UDS Components file key: `1XJoUJgtNpw4R0IIT3VjoK`

## Required inspection before updating docs

Before modifying a component spec, examples, code, CSS, or status based on
Figma, inspect the actual Figma node data:

1. Run the Figma preflight from `uds-figma-preflight.mdc`.
2. Locate the component page by normalized name.
3. Identify the canonical node(s):
   - component set
   - default variant
   - example frame(s)
   - anatomy/spec frame, if present
   - state matrix, if present
4. Traverse the node tree:
   - node IDs
   - node types
   - layer names
   - visible/hidden state
   - child hierarchy
   - component set / component / instance relationships
   - nested component instances
   - text nodes and labels
   - icon layer names or Material Symbols names
   - auto-layout direction, gap, padding, sizing modes
   - constraints
   - fills, strokes, radii, effects
   - bound variables and text styles
5. Extract the exact variant-property matrix from component sets.
6. Extract token bindings and map them to CSS tokens using
   `uds-token-architecture.mdc`.
7. Compare findings against:
   - `uds-docs/uds/components/<component>/spec.json`
   - `uds-docs/uds/components/<component>/<component>.css`
   - `uds-docs/uds/components/<component>/examples/*.html`
   - `uds-docs/uds/components/<component>/status.json` (the `current` field — replaces the legacy `COMPONENT_STATUS` table)

## Read strategy — metadata-first, inspect sets not assemblies

A deeply-composed component — especially a container-of-N (a table with
`Columns=N` / `Rows=N` axes, a list/grid, or any page carrying fully
assembled example instances) — will explode a naive recursive
`get_design_context` traversal into thousands of nodes and can run many
minutes with no output. Order the reads:

1. Start with `get_metadata` on the PAGE node. One call returns the whole
   structural map (ids, types, names, sizes) — every component set,
   sub-component set, variant name and count. Read it before any deep read.
2. Read SET definitions, never the assembled instance. Pull the variant
   matrix, anatomy, and token bindings from each component SET and
   `_udc-<id>_*` sub-component set node directly. Do NOT recursively expand
   an assembled container-of-N — the column × row × cell-type fan-out is
   the blow-up; the set definitions already hold the contract.
3. Recognize the container-of-N trap up front. If `get_metadata` shows
   `Columns=…` / `Rows=…` / `count` axes or large assembled tables, inspect
   the small per-column / per-row / per-cell sets, not the N×M assembly.
4. Time-box and bail out. If a read balloons or a traversal runs long, stop,
   report what you have, and fall back to metadata-first + per-set reads.
   Never grind unbounded. (Cost of the miss: the 2026-06-10 data-table
   inspection ran 76 min and returned nothing this way.)

## Bidirectional inspection — mandatory

The comparison is NOT only "Figma → docs." Every inspection MUST also run
two reverse passes, otherwise deletions and renames go undetected:

### Doc-site surplus pass

The inspector must enumerate every doc-side artifact for the component one
by one and tag each as `attested` (a Figma counterpart was found),
`unattested-by-figma` (no Figma counterpart, candidate for removal), or
`infrastructure` (wrapper / positioning / support class with no expected
Figma counterpart, e.g. `.udc-foo-wrapper`).

Artifacts to enumerate:

- every `spec.json` `slots[]` name
- every `spec.json` `events[]` name
- every `spec.json` `states[]` name
- every `spec.json` `props[]` name
- every `spec.json` `acceptanceCriteria[]` entry (semantic match — flag
  criteria mentioning concepts no longer in Figma)
- every retained `.udc-<id>*` selector defined in `<id>.css` (usually a
  token-only compatibility/stub file after the Web Components cutover)
- every entry in `examples/manifest.json`
- every row in `uds-docs/data/component-api/<id>.ts` (attributes/properties,
  slots, events, parts, and any retained CSS-class rows)
- every `--uds-*` token group enumerated in `impl.json` `tokens`
- every public custom event, attribute/property, slot, and part exposed by
  `packages/uds-web-components/src/components/<id>.ts`
- the matching React wrapper export and prop/event mapping in
  `packages/uds-react/src/index.tsx`
- every control in `playground.js` `controls[]` and the corresponding
  reference in `render()`

Each `unattested-by-figma` entry is a finding with a `Confidence` /
`Risk` / `Reason` / `Default action` shape per `uds-figma-change-classification.mdc`.

### Snapshot delta pass

Before the Figma traversal, the inspector MUST read the prior
`.cursor/figma/state/components.snapshot.json` entry for the component (if
one exists with non-`seed:*` fingerprints) and capture it as `priorSnapshot`.

After the new traversal, diff the prior entry against the new read at
these axes:

- `nestedInstances[]` — entries removed (by `name`), entries added, entries
  with the same `name` but a different `mainComponentNodeId`
  (rename/replacement)
- `variantProperties` keys removed, added, or whose enum-value set changed
- `defaultVariantNodeId` change
- `componentSetNodeId` / `pageNodeId` change (canonical-node move)

Each delta is a finding with the same classification shape.

## Release changelog coverage

For a UDS release, component inspection is not limited to newly added pages.
Before writing the `CHANGELOG` release entry, the agent must inspect all
non-ignored status-prefixed component pages at a compact component-set level.

The release pass must capture, per component:

- component-set names
- variant-property names
- enum values for each variant property
- variant/component counts
- whether the matrix is new, changed, confirmed, or intentionally unchanged

The release changelog must reflect meaningful variant/state coverage across
existing components, not only new component pages. If this pass has not been
performed, the release is incomplete.

## Public page import depth

When a Figma component page is added to the public docs site:

- If the page has an inspectable component set, it is
  `implementation-ready`.
  - It must not remain scaffold-only.
  - Add Examples and Code tabs from inspected anatomy.
  - Add token-first CSS or update existing CSS.
  - Fill JSON spec fields beyond the required minimum.
  - Add Playground and Demo Builder coverage when the component can safely be
    represented in demos.
- If the page has no inspectable component set, it is `placeholder-only`.
  - Do not invent examples, CSS, or playgrounds.
  - Add explicit `knownIssues` and visible guidance saying what Figma data is
    missing.
- If the page is a support/internal primitive, it is `internal-support`.
  - Keep it out of public docs unless the user explicitly asks.

Generic placeholder text such as "Examples will be added after the Figma
component spec is inspected" is only acceptable for `placeholder-only`
components. It is a workflow failure for `implementation-ready` components.

